<subsubsection><title> Check your Understanding </title>
  
	<reading-questions>
		<title>Separable Form - Basic</title>
	
		<introduction>
			<p>
			The following questions test your basic understanding of the copcept of <xref ref="separable-form" text="custom">separable form</xref> and determining if a differential equation is <xref ref="def-separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
			</p>
		</introduction>
	
		<exercise>
		<title>True/False</title>
			<statement correct="no">
			<p>
				The differential equation, <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} - x(y^2 + y) = 0</m>, is in <xref ref="separable-form" text="custom">separable form</xref>.
			</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
			<p>
				This equation is not currently in <xref ref="separable-form" text="custom">separable form</xref>. However, it can be placed in separable form by moving the <m>x(y^2 + y)</m> term to the right-side of the equation.
			</p>
			</feedback>
		</exercise>
			
		<exercise>
		<title>Select the Separable DEs</title>
			<statement>
			<p>
				Identify (by clicking on) all of the <xref ref="def-separable" text="custom">separable</xref> differential equations below.
			</p>
			</statement>
			<areas>
				<tabular>
					<row><cell><m/></cell></row>
					<row>
						<cell><area correct="yes"><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = xy^2</m></area></cell>
						<cell/>
						<cell><area correct="no"><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = x^2 + y</m></area></cell>
						<cell/>
						<cell><area correct="yes"><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = \cos(x)\sin(y)</m></area></cell>
					</row>
					<row><cell><m/></cell></row>
					<row>
						<cell><area correct="no"><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{3}{x+y}</m></area></cell>
						<cell/>
						<cell><area correct="no"><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = (x - y)x^2</m></area></cell>
						<cell/>
						<cell><area correct="yes"><m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = 15\sqrt{y}\left(x + \ln x\right)</m></area></cell>
					</row>
					<row><cell><m/></cell></row>
				</tabular>
			</areas>
			<feedback>
				<p>
					The functions of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> must be separated by multiplication, not addition.
				</p>
			</feedback>
		</exercise>
	
		</reading-questions>
		
		<reading-questions>
		<title>Separable Form - Special Cases</title>
			
		<introduction>
			<p>
			The following questions illustrate some subtleties of determining if a differential equation is <xref ref="def-separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
			</p>
		</introduction>
	
		<exercise>
		<title> True/False </title>
			<statement correct="yes">
			<p>
				The differential equation, <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = y^2</m>, is <xref ref="def-separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
			</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
			<p>
				Even though no <m>x</m> terms are present, we still can group the terms like so: 
				<me>
				\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2 = (1)(y^2) = \underset{f(x)}{\left(\fbox{\(1\)}\right)}\underset{g(y)}{\left(\fbox{\(y^2\)}\right)}.
				</me>
			</p>
			</feedback>
		</exercise>
			
		<exercise>
		<title> True/False </title>
			<statement correct="yes">
			<p>
				The differential equation, <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = x - 1</m>, is <xref ref="def-separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
			</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
			<p>
				As in the previous problem, we can group the terms like so: 
				<me>
				\frac{dy}{dx} = x - 1 = (x - 1)(1) = \underset{f(x)}{\left(\fbox{\(x - 1\)}\right)}\underset{g(y)}{\left(\fbox{\(1\)}\right)}.
				</me>
			</p>
			</feedback>
		</exercise>
	
		<exercise>
		<title> True/False </title>
			<statement correct="yes">
			<p>
				The differential equation, <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = 15</m>, is <xref ref="def-separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
			</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
			<p>
				Despite not having any <m>x</m> nor <m>y</m> terms, it is still technically separable since 
				<me>
				\frac{dy}{dx} = 15 = (15)(1) = \underset{f(x)}{\left(\fbox{\(15\)}\right)}\underset{g(y)}{\left(\fbox{\(1\)}\right)}.
				</me>
			</p>
			</feedback>
		</exercise>
	
		</reading-questions>
	
		<reading-questions>
		<introduction>
			<p>
			These questions require a bit of <em>algebra</em> to determine if a differential equation is <xref ref="def-separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
			</p>
		</introduction>
	
		<exercise>
		<title> True/False </title>
			<statement correct="yes">
			<p>
				The differential equation, <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = x + xy^2</m>, is <xref ref="def-separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
			</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
			<p>
				Factoring out an <m>x</m> allows us to group the terms like so: 
				<me>
				\frac{dy}{dx} = x + xy^2 = x(1 + y^2) =\underset{f(x)}{\fbox{\(x\)}}\underset{g(y)}{\left(\fbox{\(1 + y^2\)}\right)}.
				</me>
			</p>
			</feedback>
		</exercise>
			
		<exercise>
		<title> True/False </title>
			<statement correct="yes">
			<p>
				The differential equation, <m>\displaystyle \frac{dP}{dt} = \frac{e^tP^2 - e^t}{tP}</m>, is <xref ref="def-separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
			</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
			<p>
				We group the terms as shown below. Notice how we separated the product of two fractions <m>\left(\frac{AB}{CD} = \frac{A}{C}\cdot \frac{B}{D}\right)</m>.
				<me>
				\frac{dP}{dt} = \frac{e^tP^2 - e^t}{tP} = \frac{e^t \cdot (P^2 - 1)}{t \cdot P} = \frac{e^t}{t} \cdot \frac{P^2 - 1}{P} = \underset{f(t)}{\fbox{\(\frac{e^t}{t}\)}}\underset{g(P)}{\left(\fbox{\(\frac{P^2 - 1}{P}\)}\right)}.
				</me>
			</p>
			</feedback>
		</exercise>
	
		<exercise>
		<title> True/False </title>
			<statement correct="no">
			<p>
				The differential equation, <m>\displaystyle \frac{dP}{dt} = \frac{P^2 - tP}{P}</m>, is <xref ref="def-separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
			</p>
			</statement>
			<feedback>
			<p>
				<aside>
				<p>
					Edit Note: The latex package "cancel" was breaking how math is displayed here.
				</p>
				</aside>
				No matter how we rearrange the terms, we cannot separate the <m>t\ </m>'s and <m>P\ </m>'s by multiplication. We could factor out a <m>P</m>, but that doesn't help, as you can see here
				<me>
				\frac{dP}{dt} = \frac{P^2 - tP}{P} = \frac{P(P - t)}{P} = P - t.
				</me>
			</p>
			</feedback>
		</exercise>
	
		</reading-questions>
	
		<exercise>
		<investigation>
			<p>
			<introduction>
			<p>
				Use algebra to show the differential equation is separable. Give the <m>x</m> terms in the left blank and the <m>y</m> terms in the right blank.
				<me> \frac{dy}{dx} - y\cos(x) = y.</me>
			</p>
			</introduction>
			
			<webwork xml:id="ww_3">
			<description>
				Show that the DE is separable by typing in the separable form.
			</description>
	
			<pg-code>
				Context()->variables->add(y => 'Real');
				$f_x = Formula("1 + cos(x)");
				$g_y = Formula("y");
			</pg-code>
	
			<statement>
				<p>
				<tabular halign="center">
					<col width="10%"/>
				
					<row>
					<cell/> 
					<cell><m>f(x)</m></cell>
					<cell/> 
					<cell><m>g(y)</m></cell>
					<cell/>
					</row>
					<row>
					<cell>
						<m>\DS \frac{dy}{dx} = \Large{(}</m>
					</cell>
					<cell>
						<var name="$f_x" width="10" />
					</cell>
					<cell><m>\Large{)}\cdot\Large{(}</m></cell>
					<cell>
						<var name="$g_y" width="10" />
					</cell>
					<cell><m>\Large{)}</m></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
				</p>
			</statement>
	
			<solution>
				Move the <m> y\cos x </m> term to the right and factor out <m>y</m>.
				<md>
				<mrow> \frac{dy}{dx} - y\cos(x) = y \amp \implies \frac{dy}{dx} = y + y\cos(x) </mrow>
				<mrow>                              \amp \implies \frac{dy}{dx} = (1 + \cos(x))y </mrow>
				</md>
			</solution>
			</webwork>
		</p>
		</investigation>
	</exercise>

</subsubsection>
